node.text:
Here are some of my tips for limiting news consumption so you can rest while staying informed.

My best tip is to avoid watching news on TV. It’s designed to have you continue to watch forever and often people continue to share and talk about the same things over and over.

It also has sound, video and words on the screen so you are doing all 3. Instead try to pick one sense- read an article, listen to a podcast or watch a video.

Turn off notifications!

It’s important to stay informed and it’s important to take breaks and take care of yourself.

Your body is not defined to be in a continuous stare of fight flight freeze!

node.text:
TW- Eating disorders, Suicide 

It can sometimes be easy to forget how much work is left to do in regards to breaking down mental health stigma.

But then there are comments like this and I remember how much of the world still believes they can distinguish between someone who is “faking it / doing it for attention” and not.

Mental health IS health. Just because someone is in the olympics or famous doesn’t preclude them from struggling. You cannot tell how someone is based on looking at them.

I don’t talk about this a lot but for most of my childhood, I was a competitive figure skater. I developed an eating disorder, depression and anxiety. I also developed arthritis and had to stop skating at age 15.

My physical health rebounded, my mental health took many many years to work through. I abused alcohol and was suicidal at one point.

When people say they cannot do something, they need help or are struggling with their mental health, we must believe them. Because the thing is, even if someone were to “fake” struggling with their mental health, this would be an indicator that they were struggling with their mental health.

Just because you cannot “see” someone’s mental health diagnosis in an X-ray, doesn’t mean it isn’t real.

I’m fact, it often takes even more courage to admit it because of this stigma.

Standing with you Simone Biles!

#simonebiles #olympics2021 #mentalhealthstigma #mentalhealthawareness

node.text:
Have you ever thought, I just want to find my PURPOSE in life!
⠀
Then I’ll be happy, fulfilled, fill in the blank!
⠀⠀
I have some maybe unfortunate news for you...
⠀
Your purpose is not something you DISCOVER. Your purpose is something you CREATE.
⠀⠀
You get to decide and say “this is my purpose” and “this is what my life is for” AND you can change your mind.
⠀
Start by doing things that light you up and fill you with joy. Things that make you feel like your most expressed version of yourself.
⠀
Start with what you WANT your purpose to be.
⠀⠀
You don’t have to be the best at something for it to be your purpose, you just need to do it!
⠀
There’s no inherent “meaning” inside of you waiting to be discovered. It’s something you make up!

I often think that my purpose in life is to be a therapist. After  developing an eating disorder and addiction and getting into recovery, I am very passionate about helping folks who are dealing with the same issues.

However if you looked at my DNA, I don’t believe there’s anything that necessarily says I was destined to only do that.

I went through certain experiences and discovered I had a knack for empowering others and being with those who went through things I have gone through.

Then I went to grad school and got extensive training to make sure I could help effectively.

If you stopped searching for your purpose and starting brainstorming what excites you and what you love to do and are maybe good at, that’s the most effective way to finding your purpose.

It all starts with you deciding - this is my purpose and taking the action that follows. (PS- You can change your mind)

Start by thinking of your values and go from there.

I’ll share more about values tomorrow!
⠀
So I gotta know— what’s your purpose in life?!

node.text:
I used to beat myself up a lot for my thoughts.

I used to think that if I thought something negative or mean about myself that I was a negative or mean person.

When I was getting sober I used to beat myself up for wanting to drink, and shaming myself only made me want to drink more. Same with getting into recovery from my eating disorder.

I want you to know, you are NOT your thoughts. You have thoughts. We all have random thoughts. They don’t mean anything about you.

This is especially true for those with OCD who tend to have a lot more intrusive thoughts.

Stop shaming yourself for what you think.

Instead, try to be compassionate towards yourself. Thoughts are just thoughts. We don’t have control over our automatic thoughts, but we can start to practice which thoughts we listen to and take seriously.

Have you struggled with this?

node.text:
If there’s one thing I could tell myself it would be this.

We all hear to not shame ourselves, but it was not until I started figuring out that shaming myself and beating myself up was the actual thing that was PREVENTING me from changing.

For most of my life, I really struggled with beating myself up. I felt I deserved to be punished. I engaged in cutting, restricting, binging, purging, drinking — and this was all a way to punishing myself.

I got trapped in the cycle where I would drink for example to escape my pain but then also get mad at myself and feel ashamed for drinking and it also became a punishment.

We can get addicted to the feeling of punishing ourselves because it gives us a false sense of control - when everything feels out of control.

If life is constantly knocking us down, it feels a little better to be doing the knocking ourselves.

However I’ve seen time and time again, that shame keeps us very stuck. Shame shuts us down. In order to heal, we have to start working through shame.

Ask yourself this question. What if shame is keeping you stuck? If you tried this on, would it make a difference in helping you not beat yourself up?

Would love to hear from you all!
